Although the Dead and a relative handful of other artists allow taping and
trading, I'd bet that the majority of P2P is in fact violating copyright.
Even if the material being exchanged is a fan's live recording rather than a
commercial release it's still protected by copyright, so a torrent network
that prohibits commercial releases is still facilitating copyright violation
if its members are torrenting 30-year-old live bootlegs without permission
from the artist and/or their label.

On the other hand Pearl Jam demonstrated what to do about bootlegging when
they released the shows from their 2000 tour direct to fans, they sold two
and a half million copies.  The Who sell CDs and DVDs of their shows (since
2002) with the profits going to charity.  A lot of other bands offer live
souvenir recordings either right after the show or by mail, and that cuts
off bootleggers at the knees.  Some bands even make an effort to unearth
ancient recordings, clean them up and sell them to their fans so even
unauthorized traffic in their old material is diminished.  So there is
plenty of evidence that fans will buy music if it is offered to them,
they'll turn to bootlegs only when that's their only recourse.

Many artists benefited greatly from bootlegs and trading in their early
years, Bruce Springsteen and Metallica are two that come to mind; their
views changed later once they were commercially successful.  All things
considered the whole issue of bootlegging (commercial or amateur) is not as
simple as the music labels would have you believe.  The labels helped create
the underground market by failing to provide fans with the music they
wanted--some famous official live releases came about because the labels
were embarrassed by bootleggers doing a better job of meeting the public's
demand for live releases, e.g. Live at Leeds or Get Your Ya Yas Out or the
Basement Tapes.

If such a law as described in this article was aimed strictly at those
copying commercial albums and movies then it wouldn't bother me, I think
people who copy commercially available music are stealing, and claiming the
new Ray Davies album is an import so it doesn't count is a feeble excuse.
But the entertainment industry won't differentiate between someone ripping
off the latest Hollywood blockbuster and someone happy to have found an
obscure audience recording from back in the 70s, they'll shut it all down if
they can, in a way we'll have the thieves who copy commercial releases to
thank for that.
