Um, actually there is.  Copyright applies to the songwriting (which is
generally not owned by the labels, although sometimes...) and the
actual physical recording (which is what the labels own).  Which is
why bands can sell live recordings of their concerts outside their
normal record labels - the record labels only own the music recorded
specifically for the album, not all live performances.  So, in theory,
the artists could come after you if they wanted to but there's no
clear understanding of whether they would be able to collect any
damages.

Technically, by recording a concert yourself you can assert copyright
on that recording but if you try and sell it good luck with that.
Trading, where no money changes hands, falls far too low beneath the
radar for most bands to care, those that are aware of it tend to
either ignore it or encourage it.

