Not exactly, artists are often under exclusive contract to their labels,
which is why you sometimes see &quot;Courtesy of [insert name of label]&quot; when an
artist does a guest shot on somebody else's recording, the artist needs the
label's permission to record elsewhere.  That's also why a lot of old blues
or jazz artists recorded under phony names at times, to get paid for work
outside their exclusive contracts.  That probably applies less than it used
to as artists get smarter about what they sign and the old label model
breaks down, but you can't universally assume that an artist can do live
releases independent of his main label.

I also didn't mean to suggest that the label controls all aspects of
copyright, however note that the RIAA will go after a bootlegger regardless
