prohibiting recordings for others during the term of the agreement, the
recording contract will usually forbid recording the same selection for
another company for a minimum period.  This is known as the &quot;re-recording
restriction.&quot;  In most contracts the restrictive period is five years from
the date of delivery of the recordings to the record company or two years
from the expiration of the term of the recording contract, whichever is
later. . . . Since an artist's performance is unique, the courts will
ordinarily enjoin the artist from recording for another company in violation
of the exclusivity clause.&quot;

It's notable that many of the bands releasing Instant Live and similar
souvenir live recordings are not exactly A-List performers, perhaps the
labels aren't so concerned if artists who don't sell a ton of CDs anymore
make side deals for such releases, but it would be a surprise to see the
major acts allowed to do so.
